Use JavaScript to select and manipulate HTML elements:

**Common Selection Methods:**
- `document.getElementById('id')` - Select by ID
- `document.querySelector('.class')` - Select by CSS class
- `document.querySelectorAll('div')` - Select multiple elements

**Example:**
```javascript
// Select element by ID
const title = document.getElementById('pageTitle');
title.textContent = 'New Title';

// Select by class
const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');
buttons.forEach(btn => {
  btn.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
});
```

**Best Practice:**
- Store selected elements in variables for reuse
- Use specific selectors for better performance

Respond to user actions:

**Common Events:**
- `click` - Mouse click
- `submit` - Form submission
- `keydown` - Keyboard press
- `mouseover` - Mouse hover

**Event Listeners:**
```javascript
const button = document.getElementById('myButton');
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  alert('Button clicked!');
});

// Arrow function
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Clicked!');
});
```

**Event Object:**
```javascript
function handleClick(event) {
  console.log('Target:', event.target);
  event.preventDefault(); // Stop default action
}
```

**Best Practice:**
- Use specific event types
- Remove event listeners when no longer needed
- Use event delegation for multiple elements
